{"title_page": "Danishka Esterhazy", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian screenwriter and film director}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Danishka Esterhazy\n| image       = Danishka Esterhazy.jpg\n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = 1969\n| birth_place = [[Winnipeg]], [[Manitoba]], Canada\n| nationality = [[Canadians|Canadian]]\n| occupation  = Writer, director\n| known_for   = [[Black Field]], [[Alexis Kochan]], [[Sara Canning]]\n| website     = {{url|danishkaesterhazy.com}}\n}}\n'''Danishka Esterhazy''' (born in [[Winnipeg]], [[Manitoba]]) is a Canadian screenwriter and film director.<ref>{{cite web|title=INDY FILMMAKING \u2013 DIRECTING with DANISHKA ESTERHAZY |url=http://www.winnipegfilmgroup.com/indy_filmmaking_directing_with_danishka_esterhazy.aspx |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130630160902/http://www.winnipegfilmgroup.com/indy_filmmaking_directing_with_danishka_esterhazy.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=30 June 2013 |publisher=[[Winnipeg Film Group]] |accessdate=17 April 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=King|first=Randall|title=Gothic girls|url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/arts-and-life/entertainment/movies/gothic-girls-95093824.html|accessdate=17 April 2013|newspaper=[[Winnipeg Free Press]]|date=28 May 2010<!-- 1:00 AM-->}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nEsterhazy is well known for her haunting stories and female-driven films. Her debut feature, ''[[Black Field]]'', won the Best Feature Drama award at Vancouver's Women in Film Festival and the Best Canadian Feature award at [[Toronto]]'s [[Female Eye Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Danishka Esterhazy|url=http://www.thrillermagazine.it/rubriche/13676/|publisher=Thriller magazine|accessdate=17 April 2013|language=Italian}}</ref>\n\nEsterhazy's films have screened in festivals and theaters and around the world including the [[Rome International Film Festival]], the [[Puchon International Film Festival]] in South Korea, the Short Film Festival of [[India]], [[La Maison Rouge]] in Paris and K\u00f6lner Filmhaus in Germany.<ref>{{cite web|title=Manitoban Gothic|url=http://uniter.ca/view/4120/|publisher=The Uniter|accessdate=17 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nHer films have been broadcast on [[CBC Television]], [[Bravo (Canada)|Bravo]] and [[Super Channel (Canada)|Super Channel]]. Danishka is also a recipient of the prestigious Kodak New Vision Award for Most Promising Female Canadian Director awarded by [[Women in Film and Television]] Toronto. She also won the UBC Creative Writing Award for Best Screenplay at the 2015 Vancouver International Women in Film Festival.<ref>{{cite web|title=DANISHKA ESTERHAZY WINS UBC CREATIVE WRITING AWARD FOR BEST SCREENPLAY|url=http://reelwest.com/Danishka-Esterhazy_UBC_Award|website=ReelWest|accessdate=9 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150411005850/http://reelwest.com/Danishka-Esterhazy_UBC_Award|archive-date=11 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nEsterhazy graduated from the [[Canadian Film Centre]] and the [[National Screen Institute]].<ref>{{cite web|title=WAG Screening Danishka Esterhazy Films|url=http://wag.ca/about/press/media-releases/read,release/214/wag-screening-danishka-esterhazy-films|publisher=wag.ca|accessdate=17 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Director===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Notes\n|-\n| 2002 || ''Embowered''  || short\n|-\n| 2003 || ''Endings''  || \n|-\n| 2004 || ''Threefold'' || short video\n|-\n| 2005 || ''The Snow Queen'' || short\n|-\n| 2006 || ''Protection'' || short\n|-\n| 2009 || ''The Red Hood'' || short\n|-\n| 2009 || ''Infectious'' || short\n|-\n| 2009 || ''[[Black Field]]'' || \n|-\n| 2010 || ''Suddenly Ever After'' || \n|-\n| 2011 || ''Where the Funny Comes From'' || TV series\n|-\n| 2011 || ''The Trials of Rasputin'' ||\n|-\n| 2011 || ''Bullies \u2013 Not Cool!'' || TV series\n|-\n| 2012 || ''Fallen'' || short\n|-\n| 2013 || ''H and G'' || \n|-\n| 2018 || ''[[Level 16]]'' || \n|-\n| 2019 || ''[[The Banana Splits Movie]]'' ||\n|-\n| 2020 || ''[[Vagrant Queen (TV series)|Vagrant Queen]]'' || TV series\n|}\n\n===Writer===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Notes\n|-\n| 2004 || ''Threefold'' || short video\n|-\n| 2005 || ''The Snow Queen'' || short\n|-\n| 2006 || ''Protection'' || short\n|-\n| 2009 || ''The Red Hood'' || short\n|-\n| 2009 || ''Infectious'' || short\n|-\n| 2009 || ''[[Black Field]]'' || \n|-\n| 2012 || ''Fallen'' || short\n|-\n| 2013 || ''H and G'' || \n|-\n| 2018 || ''[[Level 16]]'' || \n|}\n\n;Producer\n* ''Dracula: Pages from a Virgin's Diary'' (2002)\n* ''Embowered'' (2002)\n* ''Fancy, Fancy Being Rich'' (2002)\n* ''Threefold'' (2004)\n* ''Protection'' (2006)\n* ''Infectious'' (2009)\n* ''Fallen'' (2009)\n* ''H and G'' (2013)\n\n;Editor\n* ''Threefold'' (2004)\n* ''Protection'' (2006)\n* ''Young Ligaw'' (2011)\n* ''Bullies \u2013 Not Cool!'' (2011)\n* ''Fallen'' (2012)\n\n==Awards==\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| 2010\n| Toronto Female Eye Film Festival\n| Best Canadian Feature for: ''[[Black Field]]''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| 2013\n| [[Women in Film and Television International]]\n| Most Promising Female Canadian Director\n| {{won}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0261629|Danishka Esterhazy}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Esterhazy, Danishka}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Canadian women film directors]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Winnipeg]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Writers from Winnipeg]]\n[[Category:Canadian women screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Canadian Film Centre alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian screenwriters]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian women writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian screenwriter and film director}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Danishka Esterhazy\n| image       = Danishka Esterhazy.jpg\n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = 1969\n| birth_place = [[Winnipeg]], [[Manitoba]], Canada\n| nationality = [[Canadians|Canadian]]\n| occupation  = Writer, director\n| known_for   = [[Black Field]], [[Alexis Kochan]], [[Sara Canning]]\n| website     = {{url|danishkaesterhazy.com}}\n}}\n'''Danishka Esterhazy''' (born in [[Winnipeg]], [[Manitoba]]) is a Canadian screenwriter and film director.<ref>{{cite web|title=INDY FILMMAKING \u2013 DIRECTING with DANISHKA ESTERHAZY |url=http://www.winnipegfilmgroup.com/indy_filmmaking_directing_with_danishka_esterhazy.aspx |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130630160902/http://www.winnipegfilmgroup.com/indy_filmmaking_directing_with_danishka_esterhazy.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=30 June 2013 |publisher=[[Winnipeg Film Group]] |accessdate=17 April 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=King|first=Randall|title=Gothic girls|url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/arts-and-life/entertainment/movies/gothic-girls-95093824.html|accessdate=17 April 2013|newspaper=[[Winnipeg Free Press]]|date=28 May 2010<!-- 1:00 AM-->}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nEsterhazy is well known for her haunting stories and female-driven films. Her debut feature, ''[[Black Field]]'', won the Best Feature Drama award at Vancouver's Women in Film Festival and the Best Canadian Feature award at [[Toronto]]'s [[Female Eye Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Danishka Esterhazy|url=http://www.thrillermagazine.it/rubriche/13676/|publisher=Thriller magazine|accessdate=17 April 2013|language=Italian}}</ref>\n\nEsterhazy's films have screened in festivals and theaters and around the world including the [[Rome International Film Festival]], the [[Puchon International Film Festival]] in South Korea, the Short Film Festival of [[India]], [[La Maison Rouge]] in Paris and K\u00f6lner Filmhaus in Germany.<ref>{{cite web|title=Manitoban Gothic|url=http://uniter.ca/view/4120/|publisher=The Uniter|accessdate=17 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nHer films have been broadcast on [[CBC Television]], [[Bravo (Canada)|Bravo]] and [[Super Channel (Canada)|Super Channel]]. Danishka is also a recipient of the prestigious Kodak New Vision Award for Most Promising Female Canadian Director awarded by [[Women in Film and Television]] Toronto. She also won the UBC Creative Writing Award for Best Screenplay at the 2015 Vancouver International Women in Film Festival.<ref>{{cite web|title=DANISHKA ESTERHAZY WINS UBC CREATIVE WRITING AWARD FOR BEST SCREENPLAY|url=http://reelwest.com/Danishka-Esterhazy_UBC_Award|website=ReelWest|accessdate=9 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150411005850/http://reelwest.com/Danishka-Esterhazy_UBC_Award|archive-date=11 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nEsterhazy graduated from the [[Canadian Film Centre]] and the [[National Screen Institute]].<ref>{{cite web|title=WAG Screening Danishka Esterhazy Films|url=http://wag.ca/about/press/media-releases/read,release/214/wag-screening-danishka-esterhazy-films|publisher=wag.ca|accessdate=17 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Director===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Notes\n|-\n| 2002 || ''Embowered''  || short\n|-\n| 2003 || ''Endings''  || \n|-\n| 2004 || ''Threefold'' || short video\n|-\n| 2005 || ''The Snow Queen'' || short\n|-\n| 2006 || ''Protection'' || short\n|-\n| 2009 || ''The Red Hood'' || short\n|-\n| 2009 || ''Infectious'' || short\n|-\n| 2009 || ''[[Black Field]]'' || \n|-\n| 2010 || ''Suddenly Ever After'' || \n|-\n| 2011 || ''Where the Funny Comes From'' || TV series\n|-\n| 2011 || ''The Trials of Rasputin'' ||\n|-\n| 2011 || ''Bullies \u2013 Not Cool!'' || TV series\n|-\n| 2012 || ''Fallen'' || short\n|-\n| 2013 || ''H and G'' || \n|-\n| 2018 || ''[[Level 16]]'' || \n|-\n| 2019 || ''[[The Banana Splits Movie]]'' ||\n|}\n\n===Writer===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Notes\n|-\n| 2004 || ''Threefold'' || short video\n|-\n| 2005 || ''The Snow Queen'' || short\n|-\n| 2006 || ''Protection'' || short\n|-\n| 2009 || ''The Red Hood'' || short\n|-\n| 2009 || ''Infectious'' || short\n|-\n| 2009 || ''[[Black Field]]'' || \n|-\n| 2012 || ''Fallen'' || short\n|-\n| 2013 || ''H and G'' || \n|-\n| 2018 || ''[[Level 16]]'' || \n|}\n\n;Producer\n* ''Dracula: Pages from a Virgin's Diary'' (2002)\n* ''Embowered'' (2002)\n* ''Fancy, Fancy Being Rich'' (2002)\n* ''Threefold'' (2004)\n* ''Protection'' (2006)\n* ''Infectious'' (2009)\n* ''Fallen'' (2009)\n* ''H and G'' (2013)\n\n;Editor\n* ''Threefold'' (2004)\n* ''Protection'' (2006)\n* ''Young Ligaw'' (2011)\n* ''Bullies \u2013 Not Cool!'' (2011)\n* ''Fallen'' (2012)\n\n==Awards==\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| 2010\n| Toronto Female Eye Film Festival\n| Best Canadian Feature for: ''[[Black Field]]''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| 2013\n| [[Women in Film and Television International]]\n| Most Promising Female Canadian Director\n| {{won}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0261629|Danishka Esterhazy}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Esterhazy, Danishka}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Canadian women film directors]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Winnipeg]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Writers from Winnipeg]]\n[[Category:Canadian women screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Canadian Film Centre alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian screenwriters]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian women writers]]\n", "name_user": "DodgeBoy102", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Danishka_Esterhazy"}
{"title_page": "Jacob Soulliere", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n{{notability|Music|date=September 2018}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Jacob Soulliere\n| image            = File:Jacob Soulliere.jpg\n| image_upright    = \n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt              = Jacob Soulliere in 2018\n| caption          = Soulliere in 2018\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Roumen Atanasov Angelov\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{birth based on age as of date |18|2018|05|18}}<ref name=\":0\" />\n| birth_place      = [[Sofia]], Bulgaria\n| origin           = [[Arizona]], United States\n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date first) -->\n| death_place      = \n| genre            = [[Opera]]\n| occupation       = Opera singer\n| instrument       = \n| years_active     = 1999-present\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = [[Z. Randall Stroope]], [[Vance George]],\n| website          = {{URL|https://www.jacobsoulliere.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Jacob Soulliere''' (born in [[Sofia]], Bulgaria) is an award-winning [[baritone]] [[opera]] singer.\n\n== Career ==\nSoulliere began his early [[choral singing]] as a member of the [[The Phoenix Boys Choir|Phoenix Boys Choir]]. Singing at Arizona's Music Fest Young Musicians Vocal Competition, Soulliere was asked by American [[composer]], [[Conducting|conductor]], and [[lecturer]], [[Z. Randall Stroope]] to sing the written solo in the choral piece and being selected to sing at the [[White House]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.arizonafoothillsmagazine.com/people/artist/jacob-soulliere|title=Jacob Soulliere|website=Arizona Foothills|access-date=2018-09-17|last=Van Kammen|first=Karah|date=2018-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.azmusicfest.org/youngmusicianvocalcompetition/|title=Young Musicians Vocal Competition|website=Arizona Musicfest|access-date=2018-09-17}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2016 Soulliere was selected to perform with the newly formed Messiah Chorus in the production of [[Messiah (Handel)|Handel's Messiah]] under the direction of 4-time [[Grammy Award|Grammy]] winner [[Vance George]], formerly director of the [[San Francisco Symphony Chorus]].<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.glartent.com/US/Phoenix/155517424923999/Jacob-Soulliere|title=Jacob Soulliere|website=Glartent|access-date=2018-09-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mapado.com/en/united-states/handels-messiah-by-galion-community-chorus-and-orchestra|title=Messiah @ Galion Community Chorus {{!}} December 2017|website=Mapado.com|access-date=2018-09-17}}</ref>\n\nSoulliere participates as a choir member and as a soloist at Christ the Lord Lutheran Church in [[Carefree, Arizona]]. He currently studies voice with [[mezzo-soprano]] Mary Sue Hyatt, who formerly served as [[Voice teacher|professor of voice]] at [[Kent State University]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://issuu.com/85086magazine/docs/85086-1016|title=85086 Magazine|last=|first=|date=|work=Issuu|access-date=2018-09-17|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and recognitions ==\nSoulliere was being named \"one of Arizona's finest young musicians\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.allaboutarizonanews.com/article/arizonas-finest-young-musicians-to-perform-at-mim|title=Arizonas finest young musicians to perform at MIM|website=All About Arizona News|access-date=2018-09-17|last=Cortes|first=Michael|date=2016-10-20}}</ref>\n\nSoulliere was the only vocalist selected to perform at the [[Musical Instrument Museum (Phoenix)|Musical Instrument Museum]] in 2016.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 2017 and 2018, Soulliere placed 1st for two consecutive years in the Cheryl Siebs Memorial Vocal Competition.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://azbigmedia.com/jacob-soulliere-arizonas-rising-opera-star/|title=Jacob Soulliere, Arizona's rising opera star|last=Gadberry|first=Emily|date=2018-04-11|work=AZ Big Media|access-date=2018-09-17}}</ref>\n\nSoulliere received the $500 [[scholarship]] and performed as the [[Soloist (music)|featured soloist]] at the Desert Hills Presbyterian Church as a part of the award. Most recently, Soulliere was a finalist for the Herberger Theater \u201cyoung artist competition\u201d <ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://azpbs.org/horizon/2018/06/curtains-up-herberger-young-artist-competition-2/|title=Curtains Up: Behind the scene look of Herberger's annual Young Artist Competition|work=Arizona PBS|access-date=2018-06-29}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|refs=<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.scottsdaleindependent.com/enewsletter/arizonas-best-young-musicians-headline-musicfest-concert-mim/amp/|title=Arizona's best young musicians headline Musicfest concert at MIM|date=2016-10-22|work=Scottsdale Independent|access-date=2018-06-25}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.azfamily.com/story/38224567/18-year-old-baritone-commands-the-stage-in-cave-creek|title=18-year-old baritone commands the stage in Cave Creek|last=Parsons|first=Jessica|access-date=2018-06-25|archivedate=2018-05-22|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180522065829/http://www.azfamily.com/story/38224567/18-year-old-baritone-commands-the-stage-in-cave-creek|date=2018-05-18|work=Arizona's Family}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.upscalesingers.com/vs_pw.html|title=Past Winners|last=SemiColonWeb|website=Upscale Singers|access-date=2018-06-25}}</ref>}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|https://www.jacobsoulliere.com/}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Soulliere, Jacob}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Sofia]]\n[[Category:Bulgarian opera singers]]\n[[Category:Bulgarian male singers]]\n[[Category:Operatic baritones]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n{{notability|