17}}</ref>\n\nSoulliere received the $500 [[scholarship]] and performed as the [[Soloist (music)|featured soloist]] at the Desert Hills Presbyterian Church as a part of the award. Most recently, Soulliere was a finalist for the Herberger Theater \u201cyoung artist competition\u201d <ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://azpbs.org/horizon/2018/06/curtains-up-herberger-young-artist-competition-2/|title=Curtains Up: Behind the scene look of Herberger's annual Young Artist Competition|work=Arizona PBS|access-date=2018-06-29}}</ref>\n\n== Reference ==\n{{Reflist|refs=<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.scottsdaleindependent.com/enewsletter/arizonas-best-young-musicians-headline-musicfest-concert-mim/amp/|title=Arizona's best young musicians headline Musicfest concert at MIM|date=2016-10-22|work=Scottsdale Independent|access-date=2018-06-25}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.azfamily.com/story/38224567/18-year-old-baritone-commands-the-stage-in-cave-creek|title=18-year-old baritone commands the stage in Cave Creek|last=Parsons|first=Jessica|access-date=2018-06-25|archivedate=2018-05-22|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180522065829/http://www.azfamily.com/story/38224567/18-year-old-baritone-commands-the-stage-in-cave-creek|date=2018-05-18|work=Arizona's Family}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.upscalesingers.com/vs_pw.html|title=Past Winners|last=SemiColonWeb|website=Upscale Singers|access-date=2018-06-25}}</ref>}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|https://www.jacobsoulliere.com/}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Soulliere, Jacob}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Sofia]]\n[[Category:Bulgarian opera singers]]\n[[Category:Bulgarian male singers]]\n[[Category:Operatic baritones]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control, addedorphantag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jacob_Soulliere"}
{"title_page": "John Scolvus", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = John Scolvus\n| image         = John of Kolno.jpg\n| alt           = \n| caption       = Fictionalized portrait by 20th-century Polish artist [[Arthur Szyk]]\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = about 1435\n| birth_place   = probably [[Kolno]], [[Duchy of Masovia]]\n| death_date    = about 1484\n| alma_mater    = [[Jagiellonian University|University of Krak\u00f3w]]\n| nationality   = \n| other_names   = John of Kolno\n| occupation    = [[List of maritime explorers|Maritime explorer]]\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''John Scolvus''' or '''John of Kolno''' may have been a navigator of the late 15th century. It has been claimed he was among a group of early [[Europe]]ans to reach the shores of the [[Americas]] [[Pre-Columbian trans-oceanic contact|prior to Columbus]], arriving in 1476 as steersman of [[Didrik Pining]], although this view is not supported by contemporary evidence,<ref>''So, presumably, had Johannes Scolvus. .... We unfortunately know very little about Pothurst, and even less about Scolvus.'', Thomas L. Hughes, \"[http://www.ghi-dc.org/publications/ghipubs/bu/033/79.pdf The German Discovery of America: A Review of the Controversy over Didrik Pining\u2019s Voyage of Exploration in 1473 in the North Atlantic] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927204928/http://www.ghi-dc.org/publications/ghipubs/bu/033/79.pdf |date=2007-09-27 }}\", in: ''[[German Historical Institute]] Bulletin'', No. 33 (Fall 2003)</ref> and as he is not mentioned contemporaneously, his identity and even existence have been disputed.\n\n==The Pining expedition==\n{{main|Didrik Pining}}\nIt has been claimed that in the 1470s, a fleet of several Danish ships sponsored by [[Christian I of Denmark]] set sail from [[Norway]] westwards to [[Greenland]]. There was such a fleet in 1473 or 1476, commanded by John of Kolno, supposed to be a Polish navigator at the service of the king of Denmark. According to speculations lacking surviving written references, the fleet was commanded by two Baltic sailors and pirate hunters, [[Didrik Pining]] and [[Hans Pothorst]], possibly also including the [[Portugal|Portuguese]] [[Jo\u00e3o Vaz Corte-Real]] on one of the journeys. It has been claimed that from the Western coast of Greenland they may have reached the North American mainland. The story can not be verified today, since the only surviving records tell us that Pothorst and Pining saw a \"rocky island called Hvitsark, halfway between Iceland and Greenland\" in 1494, as described by Samuel Eliot Morison in his \"The European Discovery of America, The Northern Voyages\". John of Kolno (\"Jan z Kolna\" in Polish, eventually \"Jan Scolvo\") by contrast, was a navigator who led a Danish fleet to the coast of Labrador in 1476, or even 1473, according to one source, at the command of Christian I of Denmark.\n\n==Sources for his alleged existence==\nIt is not certain if John Scolvus really existed and whether he reached America aboard these ships. All sources mentioning him were written long afterwards. Some evidence could suggest that Scolvus did exist and sailed to some location in the North Atlantic. Primarily, a 1536 globe of cartographer [[Gemma Frisius]] depicts an area within the Arctic Circle, north of a strait dividing ''Terra Corterealis'' and ''Baccalearum Regio'' from the westward projection of Greenland. Within this area is the inscription, \"Quij, the people to whom Joes Scoluss, a Dane, penetrated about the year 1476.\"<ref group=\"n\">Original caption: ''Quij populi ad quos Joes Scoluss danus peruenit circa annum 1476.''</ref><ref name=\"encyclopedia\">''[[Encyclopedia of Newfoundland and Labrador]] vol. 5, p. 107-108'', {{ISBN|0-9693422-1-7}}.</ref>\n\nSpanish author [[Francisco L\u00f3pez de G\u00f3mara]] wrote in his ''Historia de las Indias'' (1553) about [[Labrador|la Tierra de Labrador]]; \"Hither also came men from Norway with the pilot [navigator] Joan Scoluo, and Englishmen with Sebastian [should be John] Gaboto.\"<ref name=\"Nansen\"/> (In the sixteenth century, Greenland is known to have been referred to as \"Labrador\" by south European sources).<ref>Hughes, 2004, p.517.</ref> G\u00f3mara had supposedly met [[Olaus Magnus]] in [[Bologna]] and [[Venice]], perhaps in 1548. This suggests that the source of the statement about \"Joan Scoluo\" may have been from him.<ref name=\"Nansen\">Nansen and Chater, 1911.</ref>\n\nAnother possible reference to John Scolvus visiting Labrador is a document prepared in about 1575 for the first voyage of [[Martin Frobisher]]. After stating that Sebastian (should be [[John Cabot|John]]) \"Cabotte\" was sent out by King [[Henry VII of England|Henry VII]] in 1496 (should be 1497) to find the passage from the [[Atlantic Ocean]] to the [[Pacific Ocean|Pacific]], and that \"one [[Gaspar Corte-Real|Caspar Cortesreales]], a pilot of Portingale\", had visited these islands on the north coast of North America in 1500, the document continues:\n\"But to find oute the passage oute of the North Sea into the Southe we must sayle to the 60 degree, that is, from 66 unto 68. And this passage is called the Narowe Sea or Streicte of the three Brethren [i.e., the three brothers Corte-Real]; in which passage, at no tyme in the yere, is ise wonte to be found. The cause is the swifte ronnyng downe of sea into sea. In the north side of this passage, John Scolus, a pilot of Denmerke, was in anno 1476.\" While further containing complete impossibilities, the text also contain statements that have a sure historical foundation, like the voyage of Gaspar Corte-Real.<ref name=\"encyclopedia\"/><ref name=\"Nansen\"/>\n\nOn an English map from 1582 by [[Michael Lok]] there is a country to the north-west of Greenland, on which is written : \"Jac. Scolvus [[Croetland]].\". The corresponding country on Mercator's map of 1569 is \"Croclant, island whose inhabitants are Swedes by descent\".<ref name=\"Nansen\"/>\n\nIn 1597 the [[Duchy of Brabant|Brabanter]] [[Cornelius Wytfliet]] wrote in his ''Continens Indica'' that the northern parts of America were first discovered by \"[[Frisland]]ish\" fishermen, and later were further explored about 1390 by the [[Zeno brothers]]. He further writes; \"but the honour of its second discovery fell to the Pole Johannes Scoluus (''Johannes Scoluus Polonus''), who in the year 1476 \u2014 eighty-six years after its first discovery \u2014 sailed beyond Norway, Greenland, Frisland, penetrated the Northern Strait, under the very Arctic Circle, and arrived at the country of Labrador and [[Estotiland]]\". It has been suggested that ''Polonus'' was a misreading of ''piloto'' from the earlier account by Gomara which Wytfliet's writings is thought to have relied on.<ref name=\"Nansen\"/>\n\nOn the [[L'Ecuy globe]], of the sixteenth century, it is written in Latin that between 70\u00b0 and 80\u00b0 N. lat. and in long. \"''These are the people to whom the Dane Johannes Scowus penetrated in the year 1476.''\" The description of Scolvus as a Dane may indicate the same source as the English mention of him in 1576.<ref name=\"Nansen\"/>\n\nGenerally, the later sources about Scolvus are less reliable, since the writers probably read the earlier accounts and more or less copied from them.\n\n==Speculations==\nSome historians have variously described Scolvus as a Norwegian pilot, Catalan corsair, Welsh shipmaster and Polish navigator. Such claims have been criticised as being opportunistic in nature.<ref>Hughes, 2004, p. 511.</ref> Some writers (initially [[Peru]]vian librarian Louis Ulloa in 1934) have even speculated that ''Johannes Scolvus'' may have been the young [[Christopher Columbus]], and others that he is identical with [[Hans Pothorst]] or [[Jo\u00e3o Vaz Corte-Real]].<ref>Hughes, 2004, pp. 512-13.</ref>\n\n===Polish origin theory===\n[[File:0905 JohnScolvus JanzKolna SZN.jpg|thumb|right|100px|John Scolvus as depicted by a statue from modern times in [[Szczecin]], Poland with the Polish origin theory name rendering of ''Jan z Kolna''.]]\nPolish historian and cartographer [[Joachim Lelewel]] (1786 - 1861) was the first to gather all available mentions of Johannes Scolnus. He quoted a sources from 1570 by [[Fran\u00e7ois de Belleforest]], source from 1599 by  Wytfliet, and another from 1671 which claimed that Scolvus was Polish. Lelewel claimed that his name was really ''Jan z Kolna'' ({{lang-en|John of [[Kolno]]}}), and was the navigator of the Danish fleet. He also found mentions of a ''Joannis de Colno'' who studied at the [[Krakow Academy]] in 1455, and a Colno or Cholno family of merchants and sailors living in [[Danzig]] (Gda\u0144sk).\n\n====Criticisms====\nBoles\u0142aw Olszewicz, one of the modern historians who criticize Lelewel, argues there is not enough evidence to prove that Scolvus was actually Polish. Most of the works that mention Johannes Scolvus were published more than a century after the voyage and no contemporary evidence has been found.\n\nAs early as 1911 [[Fridtjof Nansen]] had speculated in his study ''Northern Mist'' that \"Pilotus\" (pilot) had been misread as \"Polonus\" (Polish).<ref name=\"Nansen\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Pre-Columbian trans-oceanic contact]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{Citation|title=The German discovery of America. A review of the controversy over Pining's 1473 voyage of exploration|url=http://www.people.carleton.edu/~dprowe/GSR-AbstOct04.html|first=Thomas L.|last=Hughes|year=2004|publisher=[[German Studies Review]]|volume=27|ISBN=|pages=503\u2013526|issue=3|access-date=2010-11-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120729020115/http://www.people.carleton.edu/~dprowe/GSR-AbstOct04.html|archive-date=2012-07-29|url-status=dead}}\n*{{Citation|title=In Northern Mists: Arctic Exploration in Early Times|url=https://archive.org/stream/innorthernmistsa02nansuoft/innorthernmistsa02nansuoft_djvu.txt|first1=Fridtjof|last1=Nansen|first2=Arthur G.|last2=Chater|year=1911|publisher=Frederick A. Stokes co.|volume=|ISBN=|pages=124\u2013129|issue=}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.biographi.ca/009004-119.01-e.php?&id_nbr=262 Dictionary of Canadian Biography]\n* [http://portal.unesco.org/ci/photos/showphoto.php/photo/4834 H. P. Resen's map]\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scolvus}}\n[[Category:Explorers of North America]]\n[[Category:Pre-Columbian trans-oceanic contact]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = John Scolvus\n| image         = John of Kolno.jpg\n| alt           = \n| caption       = John of Kolno, author [[Arthur Szyk]]\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = about 1435\n| birth_place   = probably [[Kolno]], [[Duchy of Masovia]]\n| death_date    = about 1484\n| alma_mater    = [[Jagiellonian University|University of Krak\u00f3w]]\n| nationality   = \n| other_names   = John of Kolno\n| occupation    = [[List of maritime explorers|Maritime explorer]]\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''John Scolvus''' or '''John of Kolno''' may have been a navigator of the late 15th century. It has been claimed he was among a group of early [[Europe]]ans to reach the shores of the [[Americas]] [[Pre-Columbian trans-oceanic contact|prior to Columbus]], arriving in 1476 as steersman of [[Didrik Pining]], although this view is not supported by contemporary evidence,<ref>''So, presumably, had Johannes Scolvus. .... We unfortunately know very little about Pothurst, and even less about Scolvus.'', Thomas L. Hughes, \"[http://www.ghi-dc.org/publications/ghipubs/bu/033/79.pdf The German Discovery of America: A Review of the Controversy over Didrik Pining\u2019s Voyage of Exploration in 1473 in the North Atlantic] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927204928/http://www.ghi-dc.org/publications/ghipubs/bu/033/79.pdf |date=2007-09-27 }}\", in: ''[[German Historical Institute]] Bulletin'', No. 33 (Fall 2003)</ref> and as he is not mentioned contemporaneously, his identity and even existence have been disputed.\n\n==The Pining expedition==\n{{main|Didrik Pining}}\nIt has been claimed that in the 1470s, a fleet of several Danish ships sponsored by [[Christian I of Denmark]] set sail from [[Norway]] westwards to [[Greenland]]. There was such a fleet in 1473 or 1476, commanded by John of Kolno, supposed to be a Polish navigator at the service of the king of Denmark. According to speculations lacking surviving written references, the fleet was commanded by two Baltic sailors and pirate hunters, [[Didrik Pining]] and [[Hans Pothorst]], possibly also including the [[Portugal|Portuguese]] [[Jo\u00e3o Vaz Corte-Real]] on one of the journeys. It has been claimed that from the Western coast of Greenland they may have reached the North American mainland. The story can not be verified today, since the only surviving records tell us that Pothorst and Pining saw a \"rocky island called Hvitsark, halfway between Iceland and Greenland\" in 1494, as described by Samuel Eliot Morison in his \"The European Discovery of America, The Northern Voyages\". John of Kolno (\"Jan z Kolna\" in Polish, eventually \"Jan Scolvo\") by contrast, was a navigator who led a Danish fleet to the coast of Labrador in 1476, or even 1473, according to one source, at the command of Christian I of Denmark.\n\n==Sources for his alleged existence==\nIt is not certain if John Scolvus really existed and whether he reached America aboard these ships. All sources mentioning him were written long afterwards. Some evidence could suggest that Scolvus did exist and sailed to some location in the North Atlantic. Primarily, a 1536 globe of cartographer [[Gemma Frisius]] depicts an area within the Arctic Circle, north of a strait dividing ''Terra Corterealis'' and ''Baccalearum Regio'' from the westward projection of Greenland. Within this area is the inscription, \"Quij, the people to whom Joes Scoluss, a Dane, penetrated about the year 1476.\"<ref group=\"n\">Original caption: ''Quij populi ad quos Joes Scoluss danus peruenit circa annum 1476.''</ref><ref name=\"encyclopedia\">''[[Encyclopedia of Newfoundland and Labrador]] vol. 5, p. 107-108'', {{ISBN|0-9693422-1-7}}.</ref>\n\nSpanish author [[Francisco L\u00f3pez de G\u00f3mara]] wrote in his ''Historia de las Indias'' (1553) about [[Labrador|la Tierra de Labrador]]; \"Hither also came men from Norway with the pilot [navigator] Joan Scoluo, and Englishmen with Sebastian [should be John] Gaboto.\"<ref name=\"Nansen\"/> (In the sixteenth century, Greenland is known to have been referred to as \"Labrador\" by south European sources).<ref>Hughes, 2004, p.517.</ref> G\u00f3mara had supposedly met [[Olaus Magnus]] in [[Bologna]] and [[Venice]], perhaps in 1548. This suggests that the source of the statement about \"Joan Scoluo\" may have been from him.<ref name=\"Nansen\">Nansen and Chater, 1911.</ref>\n\nAnother possible reference to John Scolvus visiting Labrador is a document prepared in about 1575 for the first voyage of [[Martin Frobisher]]. After stating that Sebastian (should be [[John Cabot|John]]) \"Cabotte\" was sent out by King [[Henry VII of England|Henry VII]] in 1496 (should be 1497) to find the passage from the [[Atlantic Ocean]] to the [[Pacific Ocean|Pacific]], and that \"one [[Gaspar Corte-Real|Caspar Cortesreales]], a pilot of Portingale\", had visited these islands on the north coast of North America in 1500, the document continues:\n\"But to find oute the passage oute of the North Sea into the Southe we must sayle to the 60 degree, that is, from 66 unto 68. And this passage is called the Narowe Sea or Streicte of the three Brethren [i.e., the three brothers Corte-Real]; in which passage, at no tyme in the yere, is ise wonte to be found. The cause is the swifte ronnyng downe of sea into sea. In the north side of this passage, John Scolus, a pilot of Denmerke, was in anno 1476.\" While further containing complete impossibilities, the text also contain statements that have a sure historical foundation, like the voyage of Gaspar Corte-Real.<ref name=\"encyclopedia\"/><ref name=\"Nansen\"/>\n\nOn an English map from 1582 by [[Michael Lok]] there is a country to the north-west of Greenland, on which is written : \"Jac. Scolvus [[Croetland]].\". The corresponding country on Mercator's map of 1569 is \"Croclant, island whose inhabitants are Swedes by descent\".<ref name=\"Nansen\"/>\n\nIn 1597 the [[Duchy of Brabant|Brabanter]] [[Cornelius Wytfliet]] wrote in his ''Continens Indica'' that the northern parts of America were first discovered by \"[[Frisland]]ish\" fishermen, and later were further explored about 1390 by the [[Zeno brothers]]. He further writes; \"but the honour of its second discovery fell to the Pole Johannes Scoluus (''Johannes Scoluus Polonus''), who in the year 1476 \u2014 eighty-six years after its first discovery \u2014 sailed beyond Norway, Greenland, Frisland, penetrated the Northern Strait, under the very Arctic Circle, and arrived at the country of Labrador and [[Estotiland]]\". It has been suggested that ''Polonus'' was a misreading of ''piloto'' from the earlier account by Gomara which Wytfliet's writings is thought to have relied on.<ref name=\"Nansen\"/>\n\nOn the [[L'Ecuy globe]], of the sixteenth century, it is written in Latin that between 70\u00b0 and 80\u00b0 N. lat. and in long. \"''These are the people to whom the Dane Johannes Scowus penetrated in the year 1476.''\" The description of Scolvus as a Dane may indicate the same source as the English mention of him in 1576.<ref name=\"Nansen\"/>\n\nGenerally, the later sources about Scolvus are less reliable, since the writers probably read the earlier accounts and more or less copied from them.\n\n==Speculations==\nSome historians have variously described Scolvus as a Norwegian pilot, Catalan corsair, Welsh shipmaster and Polish navigator. Such claims have been criticised as being opportunistic in nature.<ref>Hughes, 2004, p. 511.</ref> Some writers (initially [[Peru]]vian librarian Louis Ulloa in 1934) have even speculated that ''Johannes Scolvus'' may have been the young [[Christopher Columbus]], and others that he is identical with [[Hans Pothorst]] or [[Jo\u00e3o Vaz Corte-Real]].<ref>Hughes, 2004, pp. 512-13.</ref>\n\n===Polish origin theory===\n[[File:0905 JohnScolvus JanzKolna SZN.jpg|thumb|right|100px|John Scolvus as depicted by a statue from modern times in [[Szczecin]], Poland with the Polish origin theory name rendering of ''Jan z Kolna''.]]\nPolish historian and cartographer [[Joachim Lelewel]] (1786 - 1861) was the first to gather all available mentions of Johannes Scolnus. He quoted a sources from 1570 by [[Fran\u00e7ois de Belleforest]], source from 1599 by  Wytfliet, and another from 1671 which claimed that Scolvus was Polish. Lelewel claimed that his name was really ''Jan z Kolna'' ({{lang-en|John of [[Kolno]]}}), and was the navigator of the Danish fleet. He also found mentions of a ''Joannis de Colno'' who studied at the [[Krakow Academy]] in 1455, and a Colno or Cholno family of merchants and sailors living in [[Danzig]] (Gda\u0144sk).\n\n====Criticisms====\nBoles\u0142aw Olszewicz, one of the modern historians who criticize Lelewel, argues there is not enough evidence to prove that Scolvus was actually Polish. Most of the works that mention Johannes Scolvus were published more than a century after the voyage and no contemporary evidence has been found.\n\nAs early as 1911 [[Fridtjof Nansen]] had speculated in his study ''Northern Mist'' that \"Pilotus\" (pilot) had been misread as \"Polonus\" (Polish).<ref name=\"Nansen\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Pre-Columbian trans-oceanic contact]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{Citation|title=The German discovery of America. A review of the controversy over Pining's 1473 voyage of exploration|url=http://www.people.carleton.edu/~dprowe/GSR-AbstOct04.html|first=Thomas L.|last=Hughes|year=2004|publisher=[[German Studies Review]]|volume=27|ISBN=|pages=503\u2013526|issue=3|access-date=2010-11-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120729020115/http://www.people.carleton.edu/~dprowe/GSR-AbstOct04.html|archive-date=2012-07-29|url-status=dead}}\n*{{Citation|title=In Northern Mists: Arctic Exploration in Early Times|url=https://archive.org/stream/innorthernmistsa02nansuoft/innorthernmistsa02nansuoft_djvu.txt|first1=Fridtjof|last1=Nansen|first2=Arthur G.|last2=Chater|year=1911|publisher=Frederick A. Stokes co.|volume=|ISBN=|pages=124\u2013129|issue=}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.biographi.ca/009004-119.01-e.php?&id_nbr=262 Dictionary of Canadian Biography]\n* [http://portal.unesco.org/ci/photos/showphoto.php/photo/4834 H. P. Resen's map]\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scolvus}}\n[[Category:Explorers of North America]]\n[[Category:Pre-Columbian trans-oceanic contact]]\n", "name_user": "Tenpop421", "label": "safe", "comment": "Edited caption on infobox", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Scolvus"}
{"title_page": "Ivar Cederholm", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Ivar Cederholm\n| image = \n| imagesize =\n| caption = \n| birthname = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1902|06|22|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Oslo]], [[Norway]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1982|10|19|1902|06|22|mf=yes}}\n| death_place =\n| othername = \n| occupation = Singer\n| years_active = \n| spouse = \n}}\n\n'''Sven Ivar Cederholm''' (June 22, 1902 \u2013 October 19, 1982) was a [[Norwegians|Norwegian]] tenor.\n\nCederholm was born in Oslo,<ref name=\"Hammeren\">{{cite book |last1=Hammeren Pedersen |first1=Miriam Aurora |title=Crossing the River |date=2019 |publisher=Langaa RPCIG |location=Bamenda, Cameroon |page=104}}</ref> the son of Sven and Alvhild (Alfhild) Cederholm (n\u00e9e Knoff).<ref>{{cite web |title=Folketelling 1910 for 0301 Kristiania kj\u00f8pstad |url=https://www.digitalarkivet.no/census/person/pf01036392046277 |website=Digitalarkivet |accessdate=April 30, 2019}}</ref> He debuted in 1936 in [[Gothenburg]]<ref name=\"SNL\">{{cite encyclopedia |encyclopedia=Store norske leksikon |title=Ivar Cederholm |url=https://snl.no/Ivar_Cederholm |access-date=April 30, 2019 |language=no}}</ref> and performed in operetta roles in Scandinavia and London,<ref name=\"Hammeren\"/> including as Rosillon in ''[[The Merry Widow]]'', the count in ''[[Der Graf von Luxemburg]]'', Paris in ''[[La belle H\u00e9l\u00e8ne]]'',<ref name=\"SNL\"/> and Prince Radjami in ''[[Die Bajadere (operetta)|Die Bajadere]]''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Bratteli |first1=Randi |title=Den bl\u00e5 timen: min dagbok 1939-1943 |date=1984 |publisher=Tiden |location=Oslo |page=30}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Leif Rustad, \u00d8ivind Bergh m. fl. |url=https://www.nb.no/nbsok/nb/d7c5168c3d8e125f1c5737d0df78bd7b?index=2#0 |accessdate=April 30, 2019 |work=Sarpsborg Arbeiderblad |date=March 22, 1950 |page=3}}</ref> He also sang with the [[Norwegian Radio Orchestra]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Ukens radiokonserter |url=https://www.nb.no/nbsok/nb/7cc3000dde6c9f49574f556710b343eb?index=6#0 |accessdate=April 30, 2019 |work=Friheten |date=January 12, 1949 |page=2}}</ref> He appeared as a singer in the 1942 film ''[[Det \u00e6'kke te \u00e5 tru]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ivar Cederholm |url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0972946/?ref_=fn_al_nm_1 |website=IMDb |accessdate=April 30, 2019}}</ref> Cederholm also taught music at the school in Oslo's [[Marienlyst]] neighborhood.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hilde Nyblom og Ivar Cederholm |url=https://digitaltmuseum.no/011012918696/hilde-nyblom-og-ivar-cederholm |website=DigitaltMuseum |accessdate=April 30, 2019}}</ref> He died in 1982<ref name=\"Hammeren\"/> and is buried in Oslo's [[Vestre Gravlund|West Cemetery]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Ivar Cederholm (ID no. 743590) |url=http://www.disnorge.no/gravminner/vis.php?mode=fy |website=Gravminner i Norge |publisher=DIS-Norge |accessdate=April 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n* 1942: ''[[Det \u00e6'kke te \u00e5 tru]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cederholm, Ivar}}\n[[Category:20th-century Norwegian singers]]\n[[Category:Norwegian operatic tenors]]\n[[Category:1902 births]]\n[[Category:1982 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Ivar Cederholm\n| image = \n| imagesize =\n| caption = \n| birthname = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1902|06|22|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Oslo]], [[Norway]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1982|10|19|1902|06|22|mf=yes}}\n| death_place =\n| othername = \n| occupation = Singer\n| years_active = \n| spouse = \n}}\n\n'''Sven Ivar Cederholm''' (June 22, 1902 \u2013 October 19, 1982) was a [[Norwegians|Norwegian]] tenor.\n\nCederholm was born in Oslo,<ref name=\"Hammeren\">{{cite book |last1=Hammeren Pedersen |first1=Miriam Aurora |title=Crossing the River |date=2019 |publisher=Langaa RPCIG |location=Bamenda, Cameroon |page=104}}</ref> the son of Sven and Alvhild (Alfhild) Cederholm (n\u00e9e Knoff).<ref>{{cite web |title=Folketelling 1910 for 0301 Kristiania kj\u00f8pstad |url=https://www.digitalarkivet.no/census/person/pf01036392046277 |website=Digitalarkivet |accessdate=April 30, 2019}}</ref> He debuted in 1936 in [[Gothenburg]]<ref name=\"SNL\">{{cite encyclopedia |encyclopedia=Store norske leksikon |title=Ivar Cederholm |url=https://snl.no/Ivar_Cederholm |access-date=April 30, 2019 |language=no}}</ref> and performed in operetta roles in Scandinavia and London,<ref name=\"Hammeren\"/> including as Rosillon in ''[[The Merry Widow]]'', the count in ''[[Der Graf von Luxemburg]]'', Paris in ''[[La belle H\u00e9l\u00e8ne]]'',<ref name=\"SNL\"/> and Prince Radjami in ''[[Die Bajadere (operetta)|Die Bajadere]]''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Bratteli |first1=Randi |title=Den bl\u00e5 timen: min dagbok 1939-1943 |date=1984 |publisher=Tiden |location=Oslo |page=30}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Leif Rustad, \u00d8ivind Bergh m. fl. |url=https://www.nb.no/nbsok/nb/d7c5168c3d8e125f1c5737d0df78bd7b?index=2#0 |accessdate=April 30, 2019 |work=Sarpsborg Arbeiderblad |date=March 22, 1950 |page=3}}</ref> He also sang with the [[Norwegian Radio Orchestra]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Ukens radiokonserter |url=https://www.nb.no/nbsok/nb/7cc3000dde6c9f49574f556710b343eb?index=6#0 |accessdate=April 30, 2019 |work=Friheten |date=January 12, 1949 |page=2}}</ref> He appeared as a singer in the 1942 film ''[[Det \u00e6'kke te \u00e5 tru]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ivar Cederholm |url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0972946/?ref_=fn_al_nm_1 |website=IMDb |accessdate=April 30, 2019}}</ref> Cederholm also taught music at the school in Oslo's [[Marienlyst]] neighborhood.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hilde Nyblom og Ivar Cederholm |url=https://digitaltmuseum.no/011012918696/hilde-nyblom-og-ivar-cederholm |website=DigitaltMuseum |accessdate=April 30, 2019}}</ref> He died in 1982<ref name=\"Hammeren\"/> and is buried in Oslo's [[Vestre Gravlund|West Cemetery]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Ivar Cederholm (ID no. 743590) |url=http://www.disnorge.no/gravminner/vis.php?mode=fy |website=Gravminner i Norge |publisher=DIS-Norge |accessdate=April 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n* 1942: ''[[Det \u00e6'kke te \u00e5 tru]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cederholm, Ivar}}\n[[Category:20th-century Norwegian singers]]\n[[Category:Norwegian operatic tenors]]\n[[Category:1902 births]]\n[[Category:1982 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ivar_Cederholm"}
{"title_page": "Miss District of Columbia", "text_new": "{{about|the state-level pageant associated with Miss America and Miss Universe|other uses}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name = Miss District of Columbia\n| image = \n| image_border = \n| size = \n| caption = \n| map = \n| msize = \n| mcaption = \n| motto = \n| formation = \n| type = [[Beauty pageant]]\n| headquarters = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n| location = [[Washington, D.C.|District of Columbia]]\n| membership = [[Miss America]]\n| language= [[English language|English]]\n| leader_title = \n| leader_name = \n| key_people =Tricia Morrin Lloyd (Executive Director)\n| num_staff = \n| budget = \n| website = [http://www.missdc.org/ Official website]\n}} \nThe '''Miss District of Columbia ''' competition is the pageant that selects the representative for the [[District of Columbia]] in the [[Miss America]] pageant.\n\nThe District of Columbia pageant, which was suspended for some years during the 1960s and 1990s, is unusual in that many winners come from outside the district. Women are eligible to compete for the title if they attend school, work, or are ordinarily a resident in the District, and many students who have won the title come from out-of-state.{{Citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n\n[[Katelynne Cox]] of [[Columbia, Missouri|Columbia, MO]] was crowned Miss District of Columbia 2019 on June 23, 2019 at [[Howard Theatre|Howard Theater]] in [[Washington, D.C.|Washington, D.C]]. She competed for the title of [[Miss America]] 2020.\n\n==Gallery of past titleholders==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"160px\" style=\"text align:center\">\nFile:Margaret Gorman 4.jpg|[[Margaret Gorman]],<br>Miss Washington, D.C. 1921 and [[Miss America 1921]]\nFile:Helen Sweeney DC 1924.jpg|Helen Sweeney, <br>Miss District of Columbia 1924\nFile:Dorothy Parker 1938.jpg|Dorothy Parker, <br>Miss District of Columbia 1938\nFile:Lucey56.jpg|Margo Lucey,<br>Miss District of Columbia, 1956\nFile:KateMichael.jpg|[[Kate Michael]], <br>Miss District of Columbia 2006\nFile:Kate Grinold Miss DC 08.jpg|Kate Grinold, <br>Miss District of Columbia 2008\nFile:Jennifer Corey crown.jpg|[[Jen Corey|Jennifer Corey]], <br>Miss District of Columbia 2009\nFile:Stephanie Williams Miss District of Columbia cropped.jpg|[[Stephanie Williams (Miss District of Columbia)|Stephanie Williams]], <br>Miss District of Columbia 2010\nFile:Bindhu_2014_(cropped).jpg|Bindhu Pamarthi, <br>Miss District of Columbia 2013\n</gallery>\n\n==Results summary==\nThe following is a visual summary of the past results of Miss District of Columbia titleholders at the national Miss America pageants/competitions. The year in parentheses indicates the year of the national competition during which a placement and/or award was garnered, not the year attached to the contestant's state title.\n\n===Placements===\n* '''Miss Americas:''' [[Margaret Gorman]] ([[Miss America 1921|1921]]), [[Venus Ramey]] ([[Miss America 1944|1944]])\n* '''1st runners-up:''' [[Margaret Gorman]] (1922), Marjorie Joesting (1926), Margo Lucey (1957), Rosanne Tueller (1964)\n* '''2nd runners-up:''' Jean Cavanaugh (1941)\n* '''3rd runners-up:''' Ruth Rea (1961), Marshawn Evans (2002), Briana Kinsey (2018)\n* '''4th runners-up:''' Dixie Rafter (1943), Shannon Schambeau (2006)\n* '''Top 10:''' Linda Weisbrod (1955), Nicole Messina (1999), Kate Grinold (2009), [[Jen Corey|Jennifer Corey]] (2010), Allison Farris (2019)\n* '''Top 12:''' Helen Clum (1935)\n* '''Top 13:''' Dorothy Powell (1945)\n* '''Top 15:''' Dorothy Parker (1938), Catherine Howe (1940)\n* '''Top 16:''' Sandra Stahl (1951)\n* '''Top 18:''' Rita Burns (1933)\n\n===Awards===\n====Preliminary awards====\n* '''Preliminary Interview:''' Marshawn Evans (2002)\n* '''[[Miss America award winners#Preliminary swimsuit award|Preliminary Lifestyle & Fitness]]:''' Dixie Rafter (1943), [[Venus Ramey]] (1944), Ruth Rea (1961), Rosanne Tueller (1964), Shannon Schambeau (2006), Cierra Jackson (2017)\n* '''[[Miss America award winners#Preliminary talent award|Preliminary Talent]]:''' Catherine Howe (1940), [[Venus Ramey]] (1944), Sandra Stahl (1951), Iris Fitch (1953), Linda Weisbrod (1955), Virginia Pailes (1960) (tie), Rosanne Tueller (1964), Nicole Messina (1999), Marshawn Evans (2002)\n\n====Non-finalist awards====\n* '''Non-finalist Interview:''' Ashley Boalch (2012)\n* '''Non-finalist Talent:''' Scarlett Shinault (1962), Toyia Taylor (2000), Shayna Rudd (2008)\n\n====Other awards====\n* '''[[Miss America award winners#Miss Congeniality|Miss Congeniality]]:''' Iris Fitch (1953) (tie)\n* '''Four Points Award:''' [[Stephanie Williams (Miss District of Columbia)|Stephanie Williams]] (2011)\n* '''[[Miss America award winners#Quality of Life award|Quality of Life Award]] Finalists:''' Nicole Messina (1999), Therese Lizardo (2005), Briana Kinsey (2018), Allison Farris (2019)\n* '''[[Miss America award winners#STEM scholarship award|STEM Scholarship Award]] Winners:''' Briana Kinsey (2018)\n\n== Winners ==\n{{Plainlist|\n*{{Color box|gold|border=darkgray}} Declared as winner \n*{{Color box|#FFFF66|border=darkgray}} Ended as a runner-up \n*{{Color box|#FFFACD|border=darkgray}} Ended as a finalist or semi-finalist}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%; font-size:90%;\"\n! Year\n! Name\n! Hometown\n! Age\n! Talent\n! Placement at Miss America\n! Special scholarships at Miss America\n! Notes\n|-\n|[[Miss America 2020|2019]]\n| [[Katelynne Cox]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cHLFtR1z4KE|title=Katelynne Cox Wins Miss DC 2019 |last= |first= |date=June 24, 2019 |work=YouTube |publisher =KStreet Mag}}</ref><ref name=\"Cox\">{{cite news |first=Sahar |last=Majid |title=Miss District of Columbia 2019 Shares Her #MeToo Message |url=https://www.voanews.com/student-union/miss-district-columbia-2019-shares-her-metoo-message |work=VOA Student Union |date=July 9, 2019}}</ref>\n| [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref name=\"Cox\"/>\n| 24\n| Vocal\n| \n| Women in Business Scholarship Finalist<ref>{{